, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1313–":"1313–Deceased","1312–1348":"1312–1348","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1337–1420":"1337–1420","1313–Female":"1313–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1420":"1420","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Warburton, Cheshire, England":"Warburton, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England",", , , England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wevers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lever   1 and 2, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","North German: patronymic from   Lever   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Lever","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname for a fleet-footed or timid person, from Old French <i>levre</i> ‘hare’ (from Latin <i>lepus</i>, genitive <i>leporis</i>). It may also have been a metonymic occupational name for a hunter of hares.","English: topographic name for someone who lived in a place thickly grown with rushes, from Old English <i>lǣfer</i> ‘rush, reed, iris’. Compare   Laver  . Great and Little Lever in Greater Manchester are named with this word (in a collective sense), so the surname may also be a habitational name from these places.","Dutch and North German: from the medieval personal names <i>Lever</i>, a variant of <i>Liever</i> (see   Lieber  ), and <i>Levert</i>, a variant of <i>Lievert</i> (see   Liebhart  ). This surname is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Levis","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Levis</i> (Old English <i>Lēofhyse</i>, from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>hyse</i> ‘youth, warrior’).","English: occasionally perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Leve</i>, Old English <i>Lēofa</i> (male) or <i>Lēofe</i> (female), which derive from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, since <i>Leve</i> is attested as a medieval surname.","English: perhaps also from Middle English <i>lef</i>, <i>leve</i>, plural <i>leves</i>, possibly representing Old English <i>lēaf</i> ‘leaf, foliage’ in some topographic sense, or Old English <i>hlīf</i> ‘shelter’."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":2,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":15,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":69,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Matilda De Wevers of Cheshire was born in 1313, in Cheshire, England. She married Richard de Berry in 1335, in Warburton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1313–":"1313–Surnud","1312–1348":"1312–1348","1